I'm an enthusiastic, ambitious, and passionate learner hoping to make an impact in the world - my hope is to utilize software in creative ways to make the lives of people better. The past two years I've been working at FEVA, a nonprofit research organization that creates assistive technology software for children with various disabilities. Currently, I'm working on a software project called Kinect Coloring Wall. Our team is creating software that, when paired with a depth-sensing Kinect and a projector, functions as a 3D, tactile coloring wall. The target audience of this software is children with Autism and other developmental disorders who have trouble sensing depth and pressure, or difficulty with fine motor skills. This project is a collaboration between FEVA, UM College of Engineering, and the School of Architecture at the University of Michigan. I was one of two software representatives showcasing this project at the 2016 SXSW interactive technology conference in March 2016. (http://www.engin.umich.edu/college/about/news/stories/2015/july/tactile-art)

Through the use of technology and this hashtag #GrindDontKnowSleep, I look to connect young minority students with the resources to follow their passions while also empowering them to feel that anything is possible regardless of where they came from, what they look like, or how far behind they may think they are.

1. Uncommon Academy - A company focused on education reform from an operations perspective. We believe that in the last 15-20 years the model for education at all levels has severely deteriorated. Generally, younger individuals understand this best because they have gone through the educational system. In a society so focused on financial security and competition, all areas for exploration and creative pursuits are suppressed. At Uncommon Academy, we see the world heading towards a path of conformity and monopolization that will result in halted innovation and widespread mental health issues. While education has regressed in the last 15-20 years, the advent of the Internet and search engines has led to easier access to resources that limited education reform in years past. Moving forward, Uncommon Academy seeks to change the role of the teacher to a mentor and allow students to use the Internet to explore and learn through and autodidactic process that is much more conducive to learning than a single individual having to use the same learning approach for every student. Our project has been initiated by creating a mentor program in which mentors guide mentees towards their academic and educational goals but let the students actually learn by themselves. We are also creating tracks of recommended resources as a general mentor service that will aid people in their learning pursuits all over the world. The benefits of this educational model will benefit the world in too many ways to describe here. I would love to discuss it more with anyone interested. Also, some more details, particularly of the mentor program, visit https://medium.com/uncommon-foundation/uncommon-academy-13547bb78720#.fi5p8k87g  2. This upcoming year I will be researching certain chemical releases in the human brain and their effects on mental health to come up with a more objective definition of the term “happiness”. My goal is to use that definition as the end goal in our most pervasive socialization process, education. By using this definition of “happiness” based on chemical responses in the human brain, education can be reformed to focus on individual and collective/societal happiness which is the only objective end goal that can be defined.

column13: #1 Project working name: “Marco Polo”   Concept: Connect local, family-owned tourism businesses in rural Southeast Asia with backpackers.  Who are the customers: Small tourism businesses and tech-savvy, young, low-budget backpackers and digital nomads.  What is it?: (1) A way to advertise tour guide services online and see reviews (2) A way to learn how to make and maintain a website. (3) A network for photography and website translation services by native speakers.  Stage of development: I have built a small, but widespread and international network of interested potential customers. I imagine piloting this concept in fall 2017. I need to find 1-3 collaborators.  The story: This fall I studied abroad in Singapore. Afterwards I took six weeks to travel independently around southeast Asia to destinations in Malaysia, Indonesia, Myanmar, Thailand, Vietnam, and Southern China. For visiting more remote and challenging places, I prefer to hire a guide. For foreigners, particularly westerners who are accustomed to planning trips online, it can be difficult to find independent guides, as many do not have reliable internet access and don’t know how to build and maintain an online presence. When I went to the Kelabit Highlands, a very remote region in Malaysian borneo, it took me two whole days to find an experienced local guide for trekking the deeper jungles. At the moment, the best way to find independent guides is by word-of-mouth, bulletin boards at backpacker hostels, and phone numbers written on scraps of paper. Travel guide books are often too slow from research to writing, publication and printing and are frequently out-of-date in their information. Independent guides spend a lot of time searching for customers, especially during the low-tourism seasons. My service seeks to streamline this process. I started keeping phone numbers and compiling a spreadsheet of contact information for good family-owned businesses and independent guides, and discussed their difficulties.  The vision: I will graduate from college in spring 2017. I am looking for 1-3 collaborators to travel with me and do a pilot study. We will schedule sessions with interested businesses I made contact with this spring. We will work with guides to build a multilingual webpage: (1) Professional-quality photographs (2) A concise bio  (3) A description of their services (4) Phone numbers and other contact information We can either build this webpage and add it to our own website, or offer intensive classes in which we teach guides how to use online services such as WordPress. In return, we will accept flexible compensation. We will offer to do this work for food donations and a roof to sleep under, since we will not have visas to do business overseas. It will be a time to explore, learn, make mistakes, and see what works and what doesn’t.  The long term vision is to build an online network in which other travelers can do what we do.  What sets Marco Polo apart: As an individual, I have experience traveling the region, contacts, conversational proficiency in the Malaysian and Indonesian languages, networking skills, and cultural sensitivity. As a concept, Marco Polo puts an emphasis on small, independent businesses over large, foreign-managed tour companies with robust online presence and advertising and facilitating collaboration and dialogue between tourism business and their customers.   #2 Project working name: “Programmable Trees”  Concept: Synthetic biology technology for targeted control of growth hormone activity in plants Stage of Development: Literature review, long-term dream Who are the customers?: Agrifood, biotechnology, forestry, city planning, and construction companies The story: In the Lord of the Rings, Tolkien describes the city of Lothlorien, in which elves live in the deep forrest in tree-houses and in harmony with their environment. The main characters spend several days resting in the city, admiring the architecture and the peaceful lifestyle of the inhabitants. It seemed to me to be a splendid environment in which to live in, and I wished that I could visit this place. The closest real-life equivalent I have seen is Yuyuan, a large garden in Shanghai built in 1559 during the Ming Dynasty. It is a meticulously maintained Chinese garden which served as a place for royalty to relax, study, and hold important meetings. Unlike symmetric, angular European royal gardens, Chinese gardens like Yuyuan are designed to feel more natural. However, they are exceedingly labor and skill-intensive to maintain, which is why countless tourists pay money to come visit. What technologies could be developed to design low-cost, low-environmental impact living spaces that feel less like living in concrete or wood boxes and more like living in a garden?  Programmable trees is a concept to use modern biotechnology methods to control the direction and rate of growth of plants. It will achieve this by genetically engineering plants to respond to artificial external stimulus to up or down regulate the production of auxin in different parts of the plant.  The vision: When you walk in a forrest, while it may not be immediately obvious, you are witnessing a dramatic battle unfolding very, very slowly. Plants are in a constant struggle with their neighbors to control water, nutrient, and sunlight supply lines. Among the techniques used to survive is phototropism. This biochemical pathway allows plants to reorient themselves to face sunlight as they grow in between neighboring plants. This is achieved by regulating the synthesis of the growth hormone auxin in different parts of the plant. The side of the plant that receives less sunlight makes more auxin, causing the stem of the plant to curve towards the sunlight. Proteins called phototropins provide receptors for blue light, and initiate the pathways that regulate auxin synthesis. This technology seeks to ‘hack’ this genetic circuit in order to make it respond to man-made external stimulus, perhaps by expressing mutant phototropin varieties.  I can envision several applications to the inhomogeneous control of plant growth. In agriculture, it is understood that there are many advantages in growing polycultures with multiple plants in symbiosis. One challenge is harvesting. A combine built to harvest one grain cannot drive through a densely vegetated area without damaging the equipment or other plants. When you plant multiple species, they can compete with each other for sunlight. If you could control the shape in which they grow, you could force the plants to grow to a useful height in a certain direction. In city planning and construction, better control of plants could open possibilities for public gardens. In forestry, control of plant growth could help develop more sustainable methods and perhaps even optimize the dimensions and material properties of wood before it is harvested.  The greatest barrier to attempting to develop a technology like this is the immense complexity of phototropism signaling pathways and gaps in understanding how it works. My idea is not particularly revolutionary. One fruitful collaboration towards making this dream reality is the work done by Nemhauser lab at University of Washington Department of Biology, which is attempting to determine mechanisms for plant growth regulation and the Klavins Lab in the UW Electrical Engineering department, which is pioneering synthetic genetic circuits in eukaryotic organisms with novel CRISPR/dCAS9 methods. The best way for me to contribute to this new technology would be to enter a laboratory as a graduate student and develop expertise in the field.

I have always been fascinated with EdTech. With open source software like KahnAcademy, Codecademy, etc. it has become extremely easy for teachers to supply and monitor supplemental material for their pupils. However it's extremely difficult to connect with each student because each is different: has his or her own favorite likes, hobbies, role models etc. I am working on a way to provide supplemental education material, but tailor the curriculum to each student user's taste. Wouldn't it be more interesting if Taylor Swift taught a lesson on the physics of sound by singing "Blank Space"? I think students would be much more likely to watch Justin Bieber explain the Doppler Effect by noting the sudden change of pitch of a passing ambulance en route to help a hypothetical, overexcited Belieber fan at a concert. I'm in the very beginning stages of working on this side project, and I understand that the idea may not be thought out very well. But I would love to hear all advice and suggestions on the matter.

column6: MD Anderson Cancer Center and Baylor College of Mecidine
column13: 2016 is a golden era for marrying informatics and computation with every layer in the healthcare and biological stack, from drug discovery, to early cancer screening, to chronic disease management and synthetic biology. My dream is to create a company that closes the loop on CAR-T cell therapy by leveraging computation for antigen repertoire selection. Currently, we've been unable to find antigens that allow these chimeric antigen T-cells to be reprogrammed to attack solid tumors, such as diffuse glioblastoma and pancreatic adenocarcinoma, both of which have less than 20% 5-year survival rates. I want to create a computational pipeline, leveraging novel pattern recognition methods (particularly recurrent neural nets, optimized for finding patterns and rules in sequences) that can identify neoantigens (personal specific somatic mutations) that are likely to lead to efficacious CAR-T cell therapies. My second major project is in studying evolution in cancer. We have very good branching models to describe tumor subclonal evolution, especially in response to targeted therapies. But no one has leveraged this knowledge in a reverse causal manner, to try to predict the onset of subcloncal mutations based on initial clonal mutations identified by targeted or whole-genome sequencing. We have very good methods for studying the process of evolution from a post-facto viewpoint. However, again this strikes me as a problem that could be solved by application of strong pattern recognition learning machines, when trained on the corpus of data of evolutionary studies we have conducted previously.
